qas.question: How many symptoms do people with diabetes typically report?
What are the most common symptoms for men?
How long after the ischemic event do symptoms manifest?
What is more predictive of coronary ischemia for women?

context: Atypical symptoms are more frequently reported by women, the elderly, and those with diabetes when compared to their male and younger counterparts. Women also report more numerous symptoms compared with men (<b0_0>2.6<b0_0/> on average vs. 1.8 symptoms in men). The most common symptoms of MI in women include <b1_0>dyspnea, weakness, and fatigue<b1_0/>. Fatigue, sleep disturbances, and dyspnea have been reported as frequently occurring symptoms that may manifest as long as <b2_0>one month<b2_0/> before the actual clinically manifested ischemic event. In women, <b3_0>chest pain<b3_0/> may be less predictive of coronary ischemia than in men. Women may also experience back or jaw pain during an episode.
